<subSubSection lastPageId="63" lastPageNumber="64" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="62.[151,1437,1150,2033]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,284,1150,1175]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Discussion.</emphasis>
Even though 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Thompson &amp; Pont" authorityYear="1994" box="[449,643,1150,1175]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Musca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="favillacea">
<emphasis box="[449,643,1150,1175]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
<collectingRegion box="[449,524,1151,1174]" country="Russia" name="Moscow" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Musca</collectingRegion>
favillacea
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from at least two females, there is now only a single specimen in 
<collectionCode box="[294,404,1187,1210]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" name="Natural History Museum, London" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">NHMUK</collectionCode>
. It is staged on a narrow strip of cardboard and labelled (1) 
<collectionCode box="[1087,1177,1187,1211]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">LECTO</collectionCode>
/ 
<typeStatus box="[1200,1270,1187,1210]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
<collectionCode box="[1200,1270,1187,1210]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">TYPE</collectionCode>
</typeStatus>
[circular label with a purple frame]; (2) 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Thompson &amp; Pont" authorityYear="1994" box="[491,600,1222,1247]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Musca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="favillacea">favillacea</taxonomicName>
[handwritten by Walker]; (3) Macassar, / 
<collectingRegion box="[1147,1239,1222,1247]" country="Indonesia" name="Sulawesi Utara" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Celebes</collectingRegion>
. / 
<collectingRegion box="[1287,1308,1222,1247]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">A</collectingRegion>
.R.Wallace. [handwritten]; (4) 
<typeStatus box="[362,488,1258,1282]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">SYNTYPE</typeStatus>
<specimenCount box="[498,519,1258,1281]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
/ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[545,620,1258,1281]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Musca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<collectingRegion box="[545,620,1258,1281]" country="Russia" name="Moscow" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Musca</collectingRegion>
</taxonomicName>
/ (
<taxonomicName authority="Walker, 1859" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1859" box="[653,779,1257,1282]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Anisomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Anisomyia</taxonomicName>
) / 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Thompson &amp; Pont" authorityYear="1994" box="[814,923,1257,1282]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Musca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="favillacea">favillacea</taxonomicName>
/ Walker, 1859, J. Proc. / Linn. Soc., 4: 135 [handwritten by Pont on white square label with a red frame]; (5) 
<typeStatus box="[898,1058,1294,1318]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">LECTOTYPE</typeStatus>
<specimenCount box="[1065,1086,1294,1317]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
/ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[1110,1185,1294,1317]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Musca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<collectingRegion box="[1110,1185,1294,1317]" country="Russia" name="Moscow" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Musca</collectingRegion>
</taxonomicName>
/ 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Thompson &amp; Pont" authorityYear="1994" box="[1208,1317,1293,1318]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Musca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="favillacea">favillacea</taxonomicName>
/ Walker / Designated by / Dear and Pont. [handwritten by Pont on white square label with red frame except first word and last two lines, which are printed] (
<figureCitation box="[533,632,1365,1390]" captionStart="FIGURES 251–256" captionStartId="63.[151,264,1294,1317]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,447,1272]" captionTargetId="figure@63.[151,1436,447,1273]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 251–256. Bengalia favillacea (Walker) (lectotype of Musca favillacea Walker, NHMUK). 251. Head, frontal view. 252. Head and most of thorax, left lateral view. 253. Abdomen, dorsal view. 254. Labels. 255. Left anepimeron. 256. Right anepimeron." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1193912/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Fig. 254</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="62.[151,1437,1150,2033]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
There is no date indicating when the 
<typeStatus box="[652,739,1401,1425]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">syntype</typeStatus>
and 
<typeStatus box="[804,906,1400,1425]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">lectotype</typeStatus>
labels were affixed to the specimen, but an unpublished manuscript in my possession since 1982, authored by J. P. Dear and 
<collectingRegion box="[1065,1088,1437,1461]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">A</collectingRegion>
. C. Pont and entitled “ 
<collectingRegion box="[1342,1364,1437,1461]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">A</collectingRegion>
list of 
<typeStatus box="[151,210,1473,1497]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">types</typeStatus>
and other material of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brauer &amp; Bergenstamm" authorityYear="1889" box="[455,607,1472,1497]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Calliphoridae</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[621,709,1472,1497]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Diptera</taxonomicName>
) in the British Museum (Natural History), London”, gives a clue. It is dated 
<date box="[270,448,1508,1533]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" value="1977-12">December 1977</date>
and in it the name 
<taxonomicName authority="Walker" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1859" box="[666,865,1508,1533]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Musca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="favillacea">
<emphasis box="[666,776,1508,1533]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">favillacea</emphasis>
Walker
</taxonomicName>
, placed as a synonym under 
<taxonomicName authority="Fabricius" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1787" box="[1189,1405,1508,1533]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Bengalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jejuna">
<emphasis box="[1189,1291,1509,1532]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">B. jejuna</emphasis>
Fabricius
</taxonomicName>
, is annotated with a “LT 
<specimenCount box="[410,425,1544,1568]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
”. According to the list “[m]ost of the 
<typeStatus box="[884,998,1543,1568]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">lectotypes</typeStatus>
are based on our as yet unpublished designations”.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="62.[151,1437,1150,2033]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
Since the 
<typeStatus box="[310,413,1615,1640]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">lectotype</typeStatus>
“designation” by Dear and Pont was never published, I hereby designate the single female in 
<collectionCode box="[180,286,1652,1675]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" name="Natural History Museum, London" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">NHMUK</collectionCode>
as 
<typeStatus box="[323,426,1651,1676]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="Walker" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1859" box="[462,742,1651,1676]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Musca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="favillacea">
<emphasis box="[462,654,1651,1676]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
<collectingRegion box="[462,537,1652,1675]" country="Russia" name="Moscow" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Musca</collectingRegion>
favillacea
</emphasis>
Walker
</taxonomicName>
in accordance with the labels on the specimen.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="62.[151,1437,1150,2033]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
The 
<typeStatus box="[253,356,1686,1711]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">lectotype</typeStatus>
does not belong to the taxon 
<taxonomicName authority="(Wiedemann)" authorityName="Wiedemann" baseAuthorityName="Wiedemann" baseAuthorityYear="1819" box="[716,1062,1686,1711]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Bengalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="torosa">
<emphasis box="[716,899,1686,1711]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Bengalia torosa</emphasis>
(Wiedemann)
</taxonomicName>
as surmised by Townsend. The vibrissa is not high above the mouth edge (
<figureCitation box="[630,726,1722,1747]" captionStart="FIGURES 251–256" captionStartId="63.[151,264,1294,1317]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,447,1272]" captionTargetId="figure@63.[151,1436,447,1273]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 251–256. Bengalia favillacea (Walker) (lectotype of Musca favillacea Walker, NHMUK). 251. Head, frontal view. 252. Head and most of thorax, left lateral view. 253. Abdomen, dorsal view. 254. Labels. 255. Left anepimeron. 256. Right anepimeron." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1193912/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Fig. 251</figureCitation>
) and there is no concavity present in the hind margin of the eye in profile (
<figureCitation box="[271,370,1758,1783]" captionStart="FIGURES 251–256" captionStartId="63.[151,264,1294,1317]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,447,1272]" captionTargetId="figure@63.[151,1436,447,1273]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 251–256. Bengalia favillacea (Walker) (lectotype of Musca favillacea Walker, NHMUK). 251. Head, frontal view. 252. Head and most of thorax, left lateral view. 253. Abdomen, dorsal view. 254. Labels. 255. Left anepimeron. 256. Right anepimeron." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1193912/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Fig. 252</figureCitation>
). The anepimeron agrees with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Wiedemann" baseAuthorityYear="1819" box="[719,821,1759,1782]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Bengalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="torosa">
<emphasis box="[719,821,1759,1782]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">B. torosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having only pale setulae on the left side (
<figureCitation box="[1325,1423,1758,1783]" captionStart="FIGURES 251–256" captionStartId="63.[151,264,1294,1317]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,447,1272]" captionTargetId="figure@63.[151,1436,447,1273]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 251–256. Bengalia favillacea (Walker) (lectotype of Musca favillacea Walker, NHMUK). 251. Head, frontal view. 252. Head and most of thorax, left lateral view. 253. Abdomen, dorsal view. 254. Labels. 255. Left anepimeron. 256. Right anepimeron." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1193912/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Fig. 255</figureCitation>
), whereas there is one black setula among the pale ones in the upper part on the right side (
<figureCitation box="[1141,1240,1793,1818]" captionStart="FIGURES 251–256" captionStartId="63.[151,264,1294,1317]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,447,1272]" captionTargetId="figure@63.[151,1436,447,1273]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 251–256. Bengalia favillacea (Walker) (lectotype of Musca favillacea Walker, NHMUK). 251. Head, frontal view. 252. Head and most of thorax, left lateral view. 253. Abdomen, dorsal view. 254. Labels. 255. Left anepimeron. 256. Right anepimeron." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1193912/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Fig. 256</figureCitation>
). The abdomen is very dark, with broad dark bands on T3 and T4, and T5 black (
<figureCitation box="[880,980,1829,1854]" captionStart="FIGURES 251–256" captionStartId="63.[151,264,1294,1317]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,447,1272]" captionTargetId="figure@63.[151,1436,447,1273]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 251–256. Bengalia favillacea (Walker) (lectotype of Musca favillacea Walker, NHMUK). 251. Head, frontal view. 252. Head and most of thorax, left lateral view. 253. Abdomen, dorsal view. 254. Labels. 255. Left anepimeron. 256. Right anepimeron." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1193912/files/figure.png" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Fig. 253</figureCitation>
). These features suggest that the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1859" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Musca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="favillacea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">
<collectingRegion box="[1361,1436,1830,1853]" country="Russia" name="Moscow" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Musca</collectingRegion>
favillacea
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus box="[273,376,1865,1890]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">lectotype</typeStatus>
possibly belongs to 
<taxonomicName box="[623,721,1865,1890]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Bengalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kanoi">
<emphasis box="[623,721,1865,1890]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">B. kanoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This species is known to occasionally have very few black setulae on the anepimeron, e.g., in the 
<taxonomicName box="[584,677,1901,1926]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Bengalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kanoi">
<emphasis box="[584,677,1901,1926]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">B. kanoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimen from Bantimurung, 
<collectingRegion box="[1021,1122,1901,1926]" country="Indonesia" name="Sulawesi Utara" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Sulawesi</collectingRegion>
(
<collectionCode box="[1138,1224,1901,1925]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">ZMHB</collectionCode>
), not very far from Makassar. Such an assignment is also compatible with the geographical distribution of 
<taxonomicName box="[1132,1226,1936,1961]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Bengalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kanoi">
<emphasis box="[1132,1226,1936,1961]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">B. kanoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Malloch" authorityName=": Malloch" authorityYear="1927" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Bengalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="62" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="recurva">
<emphasis box="[1241,1435,1936,1961]" italics="true" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Bengalia recurva</emphasis>
Malloch
</taxonomicName>
also has all pale setulae on the anepimeron and has been collected in 
<collectingRegion box="[1038,1139,1972,1997]" country="Indonesia" name="Sulawesi Utara" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">Sulawesi</collectingRegion>
(
<collectionCode box="[1155,1241,1973,1997]" pageId="62" pageNumber="63">ZMHB</collectionCode>
), but it has much narrower dark bands on the abdomen and at most only the posterior half of T5 dark.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="63.[151,1436,151,392]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
Should 
<taxonomicName authority="Walker" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1859" box="[285,565,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Musca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="favillacea">
<emphasis box="[285,478,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<collectingRegion box="[285,360,153,176]" country="Russia" name="Moscow" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Musca</collectingRegion>
favillacea
</emphasis>
Walker
</taxonomicName>
be accepted as being synonymous with 
<taxonomicName box="[1018,1111,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Bengalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kanoi">
<emphasis box="[1018,1111,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">B. kanoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, this taxon would have to be renamed 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rognes" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[257,477,188,213]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Bengalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="favillacea">
<emphasis box="[257,477,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Bengalia favillacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on seniority, with 
<taxonomicName box="[769,941,188,213]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Bengalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kanoi">
<emphasis box="[769,941,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Bengalia kanoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a junior synonym. Since females of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Wiedemann" baseAuthorityYear="1819" box="[151,330,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Bengalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="torosa">
<emphasis box="[151,330,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Bengalia torosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group are not very well known, I choose not to make this name change.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="63.[151,1436,151,392]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
The current position of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1859" box="[471,665,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Musca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="favillacea">
<emphasis box="[471,665,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Musca favillacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="(James 1977)" authorityName="James" authorityYear="1977" baseAuthorityName="James" baseAuthorityYear="1977" box="[948,1290,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Bengalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jejuna">
<emphasis box="[948,1129,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Bengalia jejuna</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation box="[1145,1282,260,284]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" refId="ref57515" refString="James, M. T. (1977) Family Calliphoridae. In: Delfinado, M. D. &amp; Hardy, D. E. (Eds.), A Catalog of the Diptera of the Oriental Region. Volume III Suborder Cyclorrhapha (excluding Division Aschiza). University Press of Hawaii, Honolulu, pp. 526 - 556." type="book chapter">James 1977</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
is, however, untenable in view of the fact that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="James" baseAuthorityYear="1977" box="[526,704,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Bengalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jejuna">
<emphasis box="[526,704,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Bengalia jejuna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not known from outside the Indian subcontinent (India and Sri Lanka). Since the lectotype is not reliably identifiable at present, I remove the name from synonymy under 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="James" baseAuthorityYear="1977" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Bengalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jejuna">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">B. jejuna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but keep it as an unplaced species in the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Wiedemann" baseAuthorityYear="1819" box="[683,862,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Bengalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="torosa">
<emphasis box="[683,862,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Bengalia torosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group.
</paragraph>
